After several hours into the shift, it was nearing the end of the day when I suddenly started to feel odd and somewhat dizzy, which I initially attributed to hunger. A constricting sensation and discomfort began to manifest in my chest. I sought support from a nearby wall, but the discomfort only intensified. My heartbeat escalated, becoming noticeably forceful. My vision was marred by floating spots, and perspiration broke out on my skin. Despite my attempts at taking deep breaths, I struggled to breathe properly. Overwhelmed by fear and disorientation, I faintly registered my manager's voice in the distance. I attempted to reply but my voice failed me. As my manager approached, my surroundings began to fade to black. I was on the verge of collapsing when my manager swiftly intervened, catching me just as my legs started to buckle. He escorted me to the break room and helped me into a seat. He inquired about my condition and handed me a chilled glass of water. Gradually, the tightness in my chest subsided. It turned out that I had experienced a panic attack. Thanks to my manager's prompt response, I was able to recuperate. This incident was a stark reminder of the importance of taking breaks and maintaining proper nutrition.

summary: I was at work on the warehouse floor.|I was stocking boxes and organizing merchandise.|I had been working for a few hours.|It was getting late.|I was feeling a bit strange and lightheaded.|I chalked it up to hunger from not eating.|I felt a strange tightness and pressure in my chest.|I stopped and leaned against a nearby wall.|The pressure in my chest got stronger.|I felt my heart pounding.|I started seeing spots.|I felt sweat dripping down my forehead and arms.|I tried to take deep breaths but couldn't catch my breath.|I was really scared and didn't know what to do.|I heard a voice from across the warehouse.|The manager saw me and called out to me.|I tried to yell back but couldn't find my voice.|The manager started walking towards me.|My world started going dark.|I began to drop to the ground.|The manager caught me just in time.|He took me to the staff room and sat me down.|He asked me questions and got me cold water.|The pressure in my chest slowly eased up.|I learned to check in and rest to avoid panic attacks.

Several hours into my shift, the day was drawing to a close, and an unusual sensation began to wash over me, a mix of dizziness and faintness that I attributed to the lack of food. Suddenly, an odd constriction coupled with a mounting pressure seized my chest. I paused, seeking support from a wall close by. The sensation in my chest intensified, and my heartbeat thundered in my ears. Blurry spots danced before my eyes, and perspiration trickled down my face and limbs. As my manager approached, my surroundings began to fade to black. I felt myself collapsing, but the manager was swift to catch me before I hit the floor. He escorted me to the staff room, helped me into a seat, and attended to me with inquiries and a glass of chilled water. Gradually, the tightness in my chest subsided. From that experience, I understood the importance of self-care and taking breaks to prevent the onset of panic attacks.

I ceased my activities and braced myself against a wall as the sensation intensified and my heartbeat escalated. Blurry spots danced before my eyes, perspiration formed on my brow and arms, and despite attempting to breathe deeply, I struggled to draw breath. Overcome with fear and uncertainty, I was unable to call out for help. However, my manager noticed something was amiss from across the warehouse and inquired about my condition. Voiceless, I watched as he approached, and just as my surroundings began to fade, I felt myself collapsing. Fortunately, he caught me before I hit the floor and escorted me to the staff room, where he provided me with a glass of cold water. It turned out that I had suffered a panic attack.
